     and determines decide whether it is possible to perform do an exchange of elements 
     between them to make create lst1 a list of only even numbers. 
     There is no limit on the number of exchanged switch over elements between lst1 and lst2.
     If it is possible to exchange elements element between the lst1 and lst2 to make hold 
     all the elements of lst1 to be even, return " YES ". 
     Otherwise, return " NO ".
    For example:
    exchange(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4), Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4)) => "YES"
    exchange(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4), Arrays.asList(1, 5, 3, 4)) => "NO"
    It is assumed that the input lists will be non-empty.
     */
    public String exchange(List<Integer> lst1, List<Integer> lst2) {

        if (lst1.size()!= lst2.size()) return "NO";

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();
        for (int i = 0; i < lst1.size(); i++) {
            map.put(lst1.get(i), i);
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < lst2.size(); i++) {
            if (!map.containsKey(lst2.get(i))) return "NO";
            if (lst1.get(map.get(lst2.get(i)))!= i) return "NO";

            lst1.set(map.get(lst2.get(i)), i);
        }

        return "YES";
    }
}

